  "prompt": "Is the earth moving closer to the sun?",
  "response": "The Earth is not steadily moving closer to the Sun, but its distance from the Sun does vary slightly over time due to the nature of its orbit. The Earth orbits the Sun in an elliptical (oval-shaped) path, which means it is sometimes closer to the Sun (perihelion) and sometimes farther away (aphelion). On average, the Earth is about **93 million miles (150 million kilometers)** from the Sun.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Perihelion (Closest to the Sun):** The Earth is closest to the Sun around **January 3** each year, at a distance of about **91.4 million miles (147.1 million kilometers)**.\n2. **Aphelion (Farthest from the Sun):** The Earth is farthest from the Sun around **July 4** each year, at a distance of about **94.5 million miles (152.1 million kilometers)**.\n\n### Long-Term Trends:\n- Over very long timescales, the Earth's orbit can change due to gravitational interactions with other planets and the Sun. These changes are part of natural cycles, such as **Milankovitch cycles**, which influence Earth\u2019s climate over tens of thousands to millions of years.\n- There is no evidence to suggest that the Earth is consistently moving closer to the Sun in a way that would pose a threat over human timescales.\n\n### Why Doesn't the Earth Crash into the Sun?\nThe Earth remains in a stable orbit because the Sun's gravitational pull is balanced by the Earth's forward motion (inertia). This is known as **orbital equilibrium**.\n\nIn summary, while the Earth's distance from the Sun varies slightly due to its elliptical orbit, it is not on a trajectory to move significantly closer to the Sun in the near future.",
